---
import Chapter from "@/layouts/Chapter.astro";
import Heading from "@/components/Articles/Heading.astro";
import Prose from "@/components/Articles/Prose.astro";
import Keyword from "@/components/Articles/Keyword.astro";
import SetExTokens from "./_components/SetExTokens.astro";
import SetExCommand from "./_components/SetExCommand.astro";
import SerializedExampleSet from "./_components/SerializedExampleSet.astro";
import Lexer from "@/components/Lexer/Lexer";
import Exercise from "@/components/Articles/Exercise/Exercise.astro";
import LinkContainer from "@/components/Articles/Links/LinkContainer.astro";
---

<Chapter title="Uderstanding the Lexer Mechanics">
  <Heading>Understanding the Lexer Mechanics</Heading>
  <Prose>
    <p>
      Think of the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> — also called a Scanner — as <strong
        >your eyes</strong
      >
      reading through a page. If you read the phrase "Redis is fast", you don't think
      of it as 13 characters and spaces. Instead, you instantly group those characters
      into three distinct concepts: <strong>[Redis]</strong>, <strong
        >[is]</strong
      >, and <strong>[fast]</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      In computer science, this process is known as <strong
        >Lexical Analysis</strong
      > — or simply lexing. A Lexer performs this exact task for our Commands: it
      takes a raw Command string and transforms it into an organized
      <Keyword word="[]Token" />.
    </p>

    <p>Here's an example. This command is given to the Lexer:</p>

    <SetExCommand />

    <p>The output that the Lexer produces kinda looks like this:</p>

    <SetExTokens />

    <p>
      To achieve this result we will use a <strong>Two-Pointer strategy</strong
      >. Our two pointers each have a distinct role:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="pos" /> is our <strong>focus</strong> — it points to the character
        we are currently reading.
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="readPos" /> is our <strong>scout</strong> — it always sits
        one step ahead, allowing us to peek at what's coming next.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The Redis Server never receives a raw command like <Keyword
        word="SET author Alejandro"
      />. What actually arrives is its <strong>serialized version</strong>,
      which carries metadata about each "word" on our Command — its <Keyword
        word="type"
      /> and <Keyword word="length" /> — allowing the Lexer to make <strong
        >assumptions</strong
      > before it even begins reading a Token. For example, that same <Keyword
        word="SET"
      /> command looks like now serialized.
    </p>

    <SerializedExampleSet />

    <p>
      We will see exactly what assumptions this unlocks when we get to the Redis
      Serialization Protocol (<Keyword word="RESP" />) chapter.
    </p>
    <Lexer client:load />
  </Prose>

  <Exercise class="mb-20" title="Analize Lexer Mechanics" exercise={2}>
    <p>
      Watch the animation above <strong>carefully</strong> and ask yourself the following
      questions before moving on:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        At what point does <Keyword word="pos" /> advance versus <Keyword
          word="readPos"
        />?
      </li>
      <li>
        When does the Lexer decide that a <strong>Token</strong> is complete?
      </li>
      <li>
        What happens to the pointers when the Lexer moves from <strong
          >one Token</strong
        > to the <strong>next?</strong>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      There are no wrong answers here — the goal is to build an <strong
        >intuition</strong
      > for the scanning process. Keep your observations in mind, because in the
      next section we are going to implement exactly what you just watched.
    </p>
  </Exercise>

  <LinkContainer prevSection="token" nextSection="lexer-implementation" />
</Chapter>
